The village of Pegrema, located in the Republic of Karelia, Russia, is a historic settlement with a rich past. Nestled on the bank of Lake Onega, this village dates back at least 500 years and is a prime example of traditional wooden architecture. As time passed, the younger population of Pegrema moved away in search of better opportunities, while the older generation clung to their traditional way of life. Due to the lack of electricity, the village was ultimately abandoned in the 1900s. In the 1770s, a chapel was built on a small cape in front of the village houses, and it still stands today, a testament to the village's history. Although the icons were removed after the Russian Revolution of 1917, the chapel remains a symbol of the village's past. Pegrema is now considered a valuable historical settlement and is under protection due to its age and cultural significance. Its story serves as a reminder of the many other villages in Russia that faced similar fates as the world around them progressed.

How to teach your kids from a young age on how to make money work for them. Don't give your kids an allowance. Pay them interest instead. I made a system that naturally instills the power of compounding and makes them understand money. Here's how it works and the results i got: At a very young age, I explained to each of my kids the concept of saving money. However, I told them saving is not the main goal. Making sure money works for you while you sleep is the most important component. They were fascinated by money working during sleep. I showed them that they can let others use their money. In return, they get paid for lending it. To make it simple, I said, give me the money, and I'll loan it out for you. You will receive 12% a year. Or 1% a month. Naturally, it's easier for them to understand if they can visualize it. So I set up a simple Google Sheet to track it. It shows: - how much money they put in - how much interest they earn per day - how much interest they earned so far - how much they have in total now To them its like a bank account, but it keeps growing with a daily compounded rate. They call it a "Loan Account". As they get older and know how to access Google Sheets, its shared with them so they can check it any time on their own. So where do they get money from for the loan account? We don't give them an allowance. So they normally start with very little that they have in their fun piggy bank. Typically they get money from birthday gifts, holiday gifts, and then odd jobs as they get older. The outcome was amazing. The following are some of the results I noticed as they get older: Result 1 - They're infatuated by how much they're earning per day, even if it's $0.55 per day, that's a lot of money for a kid. It also gamified it for them to add more money so that the daily earnings go up. There is the instant gratification of sorts to see that on the sheet. Result 2 - When their grandparents ask them what they want for their birthday, the typical response is "money". That's because they'd rather invest it into the Loan Account and generate more money. They have naturally built up that "invest it" mentality. Result 3 - Over the years it would become natural to think of money as income generating tool. Rather than a tool that's there to buy something as soon as you get it. The incentive was flipped to invest instead of spend. They spend it at times, but way more cautiously because there is a solid understanding of the impact it will have on their daily income. Going from earning $0.55 down to $0.50 per day is no fun. Result 4 - They noticed that their daily earnings went up, even if they didn't add any money into the Loan Account. They naturally learned the magic of compounding. Result 5 - They focus on the long-term impact of money, rather than the short-term gratification it may bring. Thank you for reading, this thread was made by @ValKatayev on twitter

Who was the first European born in the Americas? The Saga of Eric the Red and the Saga of the Greenlanders tell us a viking named Thorfinnr, went from Iceland to Greenland. There he became interested in the new lands in North America to which the sons of Eric the Red ‚Äì had made expeditions in the years following a.d. 1000. He was determined to lead a colonizing expedition thither and set sail with 60 men and 5 women , accompanied by two other ships. Where he established his colony is not known. Newfoundland, Nova Scotia, and Massachusetts are among the many regions that have been suggested, although the likeliest spot is probably the vicinity of Cape Cod. The colony lasted for three years, and during the summers exploratory voyages were undertaken both north and south. Many scholars believe that the explorers sailed a considerable distance up the St. Lawrence River, and, even reached the ‚Äúland of the Unipeds‚Äù of which Cartier was to be told centuries later. The peace of the colony, however, was disturbed by troubles with the aborigines of the region, although there is no agreement among historians on whether these were First Nations or Inuit. Bloody fighting broke out. Whether because of this or for some other reason, the settlement was abandoned after three years and the settlers returned to Greenland. During their stay in America, however, a son was born to Thorfinnr and Gudridr and given the name of Snorri. Snorri Thorfinnsson was therefore the first European born in the Americas. He was taken to Iceland by his parents two years after the colony came to an end. There he lived out his life, but the date of his death is unknown. However, it is known that a ‚Äúgreat and goodly lineage‚Äù sprang from him, including several of the early bishops of Iceland.

Traditional architecture is functional because it is designed to meet the needs of the people who will be using each room. This makes traditional architecture efficient and user-friendly, in contrast to modern ‚Äòinnovations‚Äô like galley kitchens and noisy open-plan living. Traditional architecture is designed to be sustainable, meaning that it can be maintained and repaired without needing to be replaced. This is in contrast to modern architecture, which is often designed for 30 years and often built from materials which are irreparable. Credit to Zac from Street Level on twitter for the thread.

Why traditional architecture is the best option for a sustainable future: The materials and methods used in traditional architecture are tried and true, and have been used for centuries. The language of design and practice of skills has been refined to near perfection, and as a result, traditional architecture is durable and can last for centuries. While the proportions of traditional architecture can vary depending on the period, there are proportions that are often found in nature that are repeatedly used in traditional architecture. This connects us with nature, while providing all the safety of civilisation. Traditional architecture is designed to take into account the local environment. Traditional buildings in hot climates are often designed with large windows to let in cooling breezes, while buildings in cold climates are often designed with thick walls to keep out the cold.

url_description: How do you gauge gas mark 7 when you‚Äôre using a 17th-century bread oven? Why did people 400 years ago save up their urine to help with the laundry? Why did farmers in Britain traditionally plough with oxen and not horses? These are just some of the questions five historians and archaeologists asked themselves as they spent a whole year working a farm restored to how it would have been in the year 1620. Tales from the Green Valley follows the five as they labour for a full agricultural year, getting to grips with period tools, skills, and technology from the age of the Stuarts, the reign of James I. Everything must be done by hand, from ploughing with a team of oxen using a replica period plough and thatching a cowshed using only authentic materials, to making their own washing liquid for laundry and harvesting the hay and wheat with scythes and sickles. ‚Äú‚ÄòThe variety of apples differing from each other in form, colour, and taste is indescribable.‚Äô‚Äù

‚ÄúThe culture of fruit was most successfully carried on in the Rhine Province and in Bavaria. The ‚ÄòBook of Fruits, Trees, and Roots‚Äô speaks of entire groves of fruit trees surrounding the villages of the Rhine Province, ‚Äòand,‚Äô writes the author:

‚ÄúOn German soil,‚Äô says the ‚ÄòBook of Fruits, Trees, & Roots,‚Äô ‚Äòthere is no more beautiful or productive land than the Rhine; there one finds such an abundance of wine that even the poor man may satisfy his thirst, there grow wheat, rye, barley, and fruit of all kinds in plenty.‚Äô‚Äù

‚ÄúIn the last decades of the fifteenth century an agricultural literature began to be formed, and the many editions into which these works ran are proof of the interest taken in the question, particularly by the people of the cities.‚Äù

‚ÄúThe vine grew abundantly in the Bavarian palatinate. At Ulm three hundred waggon-loads of grapes were often sold on one market day. In Vienna the grape gathering lasted 40 days, and two or three times daily 900 waggons entered the city laden with vessels of grape juice (must).‚Äù
‚ÄúWine instead of beer was the general drink in those days in Bavaria: ‚Äòthe day-labourer,‚Äô says the 'Book of Fruit etc.', ‚Äòalways drank wine twice a day, as he ate meat twice a day.‚Äô‚Äù

‚ÄúIn the district of Kelheim, on the Danube, vineyard after vineyard was to be seen on slopes that are now totally unproductive. In 1509 the city of Ratisbon possessed on both sides of its walls 42 vineyards. The red wine of Bavaria found a ready sale both at home and abroad.‚Äù

‚ÄúOwing to the universal use of wine in the 15th century. it was much more generally planted than in our times. Vineyards occupied so much of the land around Frankfurt-am-Main that the municipality, in the interest of horticulture, forbade in 1501 any increase in their number.‚Äù

‚ÄúEysengrein in his Chronicles writes: ‚ÄòThe excellent wine made in the Spires district is exported to Switzerland, Svabia, Bavaria, Lorraine, and to Southern Germany, sometimes even to England.‚Äô‚Äù
